		</table></td><td class="PanelBody" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: EQ - GONE!<a name="7357"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 15 03 6:08 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">My parents both think that RPG's and the sort are EVIL. Literally they believe its a work of the devil. ANy suggestions to prove them other wise?</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Unfortunately, if that is the case, there really is nothing you can do.  I'm a 33 year old, married, father of 1 child.  I grew up on fantasy games (pencil and paper, as well as CRPG), and have come across MULTITUDES of people who believe as your parents do.
<br />

<br />
I am also a Catholic Christian, with very deep religious beliefs myself.  My interest in fantasy games was never questioned by my parents, fortunately.  Fantasy inspired me to read and write much moreso than my friends of equal age were doing.  I can say with honesty that from the time I was 11 years old, until the present day, there has NEVER been a time in my life when I haven't been in the process of reading SOMETHING.
<br />

<br />
People who believe fantasy games are &quot;the work of the devil&quot;, are already divorcing themselves from logic to begin with.  There is, quite simply, nothing you can do to change their minds.  When you see things from their perspective, you begin to understand that there is nothing you can do or say to convince them that what they think is intrinsically evil is actually neutral.  What I mean is this:  They won't be pursuaded that fantasy games are good by argument alone, anymore than you could convince them that Jesus is not the messiah by smooth talking them into it.  They are coming from the point-of-view of Faith.  That's not shaken easily, even if misguided.
<br />

<br />
The only thing you can do, for now, is show your parents that you are:
<br />
1) Responsible and mature
<br />
2) Well-adjusted
<br />
3) A person of unwavering integrity and moral standards
<br />
4) an obedient son/daughter (sorry, I don't know if you are male or female, but I'm guessing male).
<br />

<br />
Here's the catch:  You might never convince them otherwise (with regards to the Fantasy thing), but one thing is certain: you will benefit, either way, from doing each of those 4 things.
<br />

<br />
I don't know how old you are.  But, believe me, years begin to peel away at an ever-accelerating rate!  You will, fortunately (and unfortunately...it's a conundrum) eventually be out from under the wings of your parents and be able to make decisions on your own.  By attempting to do those 4 things above, you will be that much closer to guaranteeing that those decisions will be good ones, and not mistakes.
<br />

<br />
For now, be as obedient to them as you can, as that will garner you rewards not only now, but in your future life as an adult.  Parents don't always know everything.  Lord knows, they're not always right.  But one thing is almost always a given:  they have your best interests at heart, and TRULY believe they are doing what's best for you, out of LOVE for you.  Accept that love for everything it's worth, because not everyone gets that growing up.  It's invaluable!  So many families break up because the spouses did not receive the type of love they deserved from THEIR parents!
<br />

<br />
I know this was long winded, and I apologize for that.  The short answer is &quot;no&quot;.  There is nothing I can conceive of that would change their mind.  However, when you are a (legal) adult, and you begin choosing to play RPGs on your own, AND you can demonstrate that they are not influencing your moral decisions, or destroying your integrity, then...maybe...they will see that just maybe they were wrong.
<br />

<br />
For the time being, take comfort from the fact that when you are able to play RPGs on your own, they will be a HECK of a lot better than that ghetto MMOG they used to call EQ ;)</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
